<p><b>Yoga</b> (<a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a>, <a href="/wiki/P%C4%81li" title="Pāli" class="mw-redirect">Pāli</a>: <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E0%A4%AF%E0%A5%8B%E0%A4%97" class="extiw" title="wikt:योग">योग</a>, <a href="/wiki/IAST" title="IAST" class="mw-redirect">IAST</a>: <i>yóga</i>, <small>IPA</small>:&#160;<span title="Pronunciation in IPA" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA" title="Wikipedia:IPA">[joːgə]</a></span>) refers to traditional <a href="/wiki/Physical" title="Physical">physical</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mental" title="Mental">mental</a> disciplines originating in <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> The word is associated with meditative practices in both <a href="/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">Buddhism</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hinduism" title="Hinduism">Hinduism</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> In Hinduism, it also refers to one of the six orthodox (<a href="/wiki/%C4%80stika" title="Āstika" class="mw-redirect">āstika</a>) schools of <a href="/wiki/Hindu_philosophy" title="Hindu philosophy">Hindu philosophy</a>, and to the goal toward which that school directs its practices.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4" title=""><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Major branches of yoga include <a href="/wiki/Raja_Yoga" title="Raja Yoga">Raja Yoga</a>, <a href="/wiki/Karma_Yoga" title="Karma Yoga">Karma Yoga</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jnana_Yoga" title="Jnana Yoga" class="mw-redirect">Jnana Yoga</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bhakti_Yoga" title="Bhakti Yoga" class="mw-redirect">Bhakti Yoga</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Hatha_Yoga" title="Hatha Yoga" class="mw-redirect">Hatha Yoga</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-yogaTrads1_042007_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-yogaTrads1_042007-5" title=""><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-yogaTrads2_042007_6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-yogaTrads2_042007-6" title=""><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-yogaTrads_3042007_7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-yogaTrads_3042007-7" title=""><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup> Raja Yoga, compiled in the <a href="/wiki/Yoga_Sutras_of_Patanjali" title="Yoga Sutras of Patanjali">Yoga Sutras of Patanjali</a>, and known simply as yoga in the context of Hindu philosophy, is part of the <a href="/wiki/Samkhya" title="Samkhya">Samkhya</a> tradition.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8" title=""><span>[</span>9<span>]</span></a></sup> Many other <a href="/wiki/Hindu_texts" title="Hindu texts">Hindu texts</a> discuss aspects of yoga, including <a href="/wiki/Upanishads" title="Upanishads">Upanishads</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Bhagavad_Gita" title="Bhagavad Gita">Bhagavad Gita</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Hatha_Yoga_Pradipika" title="Hatha Yoga Pradipika">Hatha Yoga Pradipika</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Shiva_Samhita" title="Shiva Samhita">Shiva Samhita</a> and various <a href="/wiki/Tantra" title="Tantra">Tantras</a>.</p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a> word <i>yoga</i> has many meanings,<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9" title=""><span>[</span>10<span>]</span></a></sup> and is derived from the Sanskrit root <i>yuj</i>, meaning "to control", "to yoke" or "to unite".<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10" title=""><span>[</span>11<span>]</span></a></sup> Translations include "joining", "uniting", "union", "conjunction", and "means".<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11" title=""><span>[</span>12<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12" title=""><span>[</span>13<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13" title=""><span>[</span>14<span>]</span></a></sup> Outside India, the term <i>yoga</i> is typically associated with <a href="/wiki/Hatha_Yoga" title="Hatha Yoga" class="mw-redirect">Hatha Yoga</a> and its <a href="/wiki/Asanas" title="Asanas" class="mw-redirect">asanas</a> (postures) or as a <a href="/wiki/Yoga_as_exercise" title="Yoga as exercise" class="mw-redirect">form of exercise</a>. An accomplished practitioner of Yoga is called a <a href="/wiki/Yogi" title="Yogi">Yogi</a> (gender neutral) or <a href="/wiki/Yogini" title="Yogini">Yogini</a> (feminine form).</p>
